A total of 105 patients (males = 56, mean age = 57 years) had both normal MPI results and CCTA performed (median interval = 75 days; Table 1
). Eighty-seven patients (87 of 105, 82%) had symptoms as the indication for their CCTA. While 32% of patients (34 of 105) had typical angina (substernal chest pain provoked by exertion), the majority patients had atypical chest pain (46 of 105, 43%). Of the 105 patients with normal MPI results, 42 patients (42 of 105, 40%) had obstructive CAD (>50% stenosis) on CCTA (Table 1). Nineteen patients (19 of 42, 45%) had single-vessel CAD with the LAD artery being predominantly affected (32 of 42, 83%; Table 2
). In addition, 18 patients (18 of 42, 43%) had obstructive CAD considered “high-risk” (left main artery disease, 3-vessel CAD, or 2-vessel disease including the proximal LAD). None of the MPI studies observed transient left ventricular dilatation or transient lung uptake after stress which would represent high-risk perfusion abnormalities.
12

Patients with normal SPECT MPI results and obstructive CAD on CCTA were significantly older than patients without obstructive CAD (62.4 ±8.2 vs 53.9 ±10.1; P < .0001; Table 1). Based on a univariable analysis comparing patients with and without obstructive CAD on CCTA, patients with obstructive CAD were associated with advanced age (≥65 years; 48% vs 17%; P = .001), hypertension (76% vs 49%; P = .007), diabetes mellitus (36% vs 14%; P = .01), dyslipidemia (95% vs 78%, P = .03), increased FRS (10% vs 6%, P < .0001), and elevated CACS (288.0 [429.0] vs 0.0 [14.0] AU; P < .0001; Table 1). After adjusting for advanced age (≥65 years), hypertension, diabetes mellitus, and dyslipidemia; increased FRS, and elevated CACS were the only predictors that remained significantly associated with obstructive CAD on CCTA in patients with normal SPECT MPI (P = .006 and P < .0001, respectively; Table 3
). Patients with normal stress MPI had 13 times and 98 times higher odds of having obstructive CAD on CCTA if they had a FRS ≥10% compared to <10% (95% CI: 2.1-78.0) and CACS >100AU compared to ≤100 AU (95% CI: 16.1-594.8), respectively (Table 3). Combining both FRS and CACS, we observed that 100% of patients with FRS ≥10% and CACS >100 AU had obstructive CAD. Conversely, 95.8% of patients with a low FRS <10% and CACS ≤100 AU had nonobstructive CAD or normal studies (Table 4
).
